## What This Project Is

This is a **distributed real-time communication platform** with two features:
1. **Group Chat** — everyone in the room sees everyone's messages
2. **1:1 Video Calling** — two users can video call each other directly (peer-to-peer)

The "distributed" part means you can run **multiple copies of the server** and everything still works. This is how production apps like Slack, Discord, and Zoom scale to millions of users.

---

## High-Level Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     BROWSER CLIENTS                      │
│  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐              │
│  │  Alice    │  │   Bob    │  │  Charlie │              │
│  │(Browser 1)│  │(Browser 2)│  │(Browser 3)│              │
│  └─────┬─────┘  └─────┬─────┘  └─────┬─────┘              │
│        │ WebSocket     │ WebSocket     │ WebSocket         │
└────────┼───────────────┼───────────────┼──────────────────┘
         │               │               │
         ▼               ▼               ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              CADDY (Reverse Proxy / Load Balancer)       │
│              Port 3000 → Routes to backend servers       │
│              Serves static files (HTML/CSS/JS)           │
│              Uses ip_hash for sticky sessions            │
└─────┬──────────────────┬──────────────────┬─────────────┘
      │                  │                  │
      ▼                  ▼                  ▼
┌──────────┐      ┌──────────┐      ┌──────────┐
│   ws1    │      │   ws2    │      │   ws3    │
│ Port 4001│      │ Port 4002│      │ Port 4003│
│ Node.js  │      │ Node.js  │      │ Node.js  │
└─────┬────┘      └─────┬────┘      └─────┬────┘
      │                  │                  │
      └──────────────────┼──────────────────┘
                         │ Pub/Sub
                         ▼
                  ┌──────────────┐
                  │    REDIS     │
                  │  Port 6379   │
                  │ • Pub/Sub    │
                  │ • User Set   │
                  └──────────────┘
```

**After video call signaling completes:**
```
Alice 🎥 ←────── Direct P2P (WebRTC) ──────→ 🎥 Bob
          (Video/audio NEVER goes through the server)
```

---

## WebSocket — The Backbone

### What is WebSocket?
HTTP is **request-response** — the client asks, the server answers, connection closes. WebSocket is a **persistent, bidirectional** connection. Once opened, both client and server can send messages to each other at any time.

### Why WebSocket here?
- **Chat**: When Alice sends a message, the server needs to instantly push it to Bob and Charlie — without them asking for it
- **Signaling**: WebRTC needs a "meeting point" to exchange connection info before video starts
- **User presence**: Server can instantly notify everyone when someone joins/leaves

### How it works in our code

**Client side** ([index.js](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/client/index.js)):
```js
// Browser opens a persistent connection to the server
const wsUrl = `ws://localhost:3000/ws`;
this.socket = new WebSocket(wsUrl);

// Server can push messages anytime
this.socket.onmessage = (event) => {
    const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
    // handle chat, events, signaling...
};

// Client can send messages anytime
this.socket.send(JSON.stringify({ type: "message", user: "Alice", content: "Hello!" }));
```

**Server side** ([index.ts](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/server/src/index.ts)):
```ts
// ws library creates a WebSocket server
const wss = new WebSocketServer({ port: 4001, host: "0.0.0.0" });

// Fires when a browser connects
wss.on("connection", (ws) => {
    ws.on("message", (data) => {
        // Process incoming message from this client
    });
});
```

### Heartbeat System
WebSocket connections can silently die (network drops, laptop sleeps). The **heartbeat** system detects this:

```
Every 30 seconds:
  Server → sends PING to each client
  Client → automatically responds with PONG
  
If no PONG received → connection is dead → server cleans up
```

This is handled in [index.ts](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/server/src/index.ts) with `setInterval` and `ws.ping()`.

---

## Redis Pub/Sub — Cross-Server Sync

### The Problem
Imagine Alice is connected to **ws1** and Bob is connected to **ws2**. Alice sends a message. **ws1 only knows about its own clients** — it doesn't know Bob exists on ws2. How does Bob get the message?

### The Solution: Redis Pub/Sub
Redis acts as a **message broker** between all servers:

```
Alice's message "Hello!"
        │
        ▼
   ws1 receives it
        │
        ▼
   ws1 PUBLISHES to Redis channel "chat_channel"
        │
        ▼
   Redis delivers to ALL subscribers
        │
   ┌────┼────┐
   ▼    ▼    ▼
  ws1  ws2  ws3    ← Every server gets the message
   │    │    │
   ▼    ▼    ▼
 All their local clients receive it
 (Alice sees her own message, Bob sees it too)
```

### Two Channels

| Channel | Purpose | Delivery |
|---------|---------|----------|
| `chat_channel` | Chat messages, join/leave events, user lists | **Broadcast** to ALL clients on all servers |
| `signaling_channel` | WebRTC offer/answer/ICE | **Targeted** — only delivered to specific user |

### How it works in our code

**Publishing** ([redis.ts](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/server/src/redis.ts)):
```ts
// When Alice sends a chat message, the server publishes it:
await publisher.publish("chat_channel", JSON.stringify(payload));
```

**Subscribing** ([redis.ts](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/server/src/redis.ts)):
```ts
// Every server subscribes to both channels on startup:
await subscriber.subscribe("chat_channel", "signaling_channel");
```

**Listening** ([index.ts](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/server/src/index.ts)):
```ts
subscriber.on("message", (channel, message) => {
    if (channel === "chat_channel") {
        // Send to ALL local WebSocket clients
        broadcastToAll(wss, message);
    } else if (channel === "signaling_channel") {
        // Send only to the TARGET user (if they're on this server)
        handleSignalingFromRedis(message, userMap);
    }
});
```

### Online Users Tracking (Redis Set)
Each server only knows its own users. To show a **global** online list, we use a **Redis Set**:

```ts
// When Alice joins on ws1:
await publisher.sadd("online_users", "Alice");    // Add to Redis Set

// When Alice leaves:
await publisher.srem("online_users", "Alice");    // Remove from Redis Set

// To get ALL online users across ALL servers:
const users = await publisher.smembers("online_users");  // Returns ["Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"]
```

