## Caddy — Reverse Proxy & Load Balancer

### What is a Reverse Proxy?
Users connect to **one URL** (`localhost:3000`). Behind the scenes, there are **3 separate servers** (ws1, ws2, ws3). Caddy sits in front and **routes** requests to the right place.

### What Caddy Does (Two Jobs)

**Job 1: Serve static files (Frontend)**
```
Browser requests: http://localhost:3000/
Caddy responds:   Serves index.html from the client/ folder

Browser requests: http://localhost:3000/index.css
Caddy responds:   Serves index.css from the client/ folder
```

**Job 2: Proxy WebSocket connections (Backend)**
```
Browser connects: ws://localhost:3000/ws
Caddy proxies to: ws1:4001 OR ws2:4002 OR ws3:4003
```

### Load Balancing: ip_hash

When 3 users connect, Caddy must decide which backend server each goes to. We use `ip_hash`:

```
ip_hash = hash(client's IP address) → always maps to SAME server

Alice (IP: 192.168.1.10) → hash → always goes to ws1
Bob   (IP: 192.168.1.20) → hash → always goes to ws2
```

**Why ip_hash (sticky sessions)?** Because WebSocket is a **persistent connection**. If Alice connects to ws1, her entire session must stay on ws1. If Caddy randomly changed servers mid-connection, the WebSocket would break.

### Our Caddyfile Explained

```caddyfile
:8080 {
    # FIRST: Handle WebSocket — MUST come before file_server
    # Otherwise, /ws path would match index.html via try_files
    handle /ws* {
        reverse_proxy ws1:4001 ws2:4002 ws3:4003 {
            lb_policy ip_hash          # Sticky sessions
            header_up Host {host}      # Forward original host header
            header_up X-Real-IP {remote_host}  # Forward client IP
        }
    }

    # SECOND: Everything else → serve static files
    handle {
        root * /srv                    # Files are in /srv (mounted from client/)
        try_files {path} /index.html   # SPA fallback
        file_server                    # Serve the files
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The order matters! We had a bug where `file_server` was catching `/ws` requests and serving [index.html](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/client/index.html) instead of proxying to the backend. The fix was putting the WebSocket [handle](file:///Users/taranjain/Downloads/Real_Time_Chat_App-main/client/index.js#418-439) block **first**.

